[normal].
[normal]              
[normal]We do not agree with the introduction of a residence test for foreign national prisoners or immigration detainees. Immigration detainees should be funded to challenge the lawfulness of their detention regardless of their ties to the 
[normal]UK
[normal]. In our immigration 
[normal]removal centre
[normal] (IRC)
[normal] inspections we 
[normal]repeatedly
[normal] 
[normal]find detainees held for years at a time.
[normal] S
[normal]everal have successfully challenged the lawfulness of their 
[normal]detention
[normal] using
[normal] legal aid. Removing the right to legal aid for such individuals 
[normal]may 
[normal]increase the likelihood
[normal] that
[normal] these cases will remain unresolved
[normal]. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]2
[normal]5
[normal].
[normal]              
[normal]The 2011 Independent Monitoring Board annual report of 
[normal]Harmondsworth
[normal] 
[normal]raised significant concerns relating to the treatment of detainees suffering from mental health issues. Since 2011
[normal],
[normal] the High Court has fou
[normal]nd in favour of four individuals who have brought cases against the 
[normal]UK Border Agency
[normal]. The court found 
[normal]inter alia
[normal] that the defendants had been falsely imprisoned and subject to inhuman and degrading treatment in violation of their Article 3 rights under the
[normal] European Convention on Human Rights. The introduction of a residency test makes it le
[normal]ss likely that this type of ill-
[normal]treatment will come to the attention of the courts. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]2
[normal]6
[normal].
[normal]              
[normal]Taking all this evidence into consideration, we 
[normal]consider
[normal] that the residence test
[normal] should not be introduced in civil legal aid cases
[normal] to individuals who are detained
[normal]. While the test would apply to 
[normal]UK
[normal] residents, its impact would disproportionately affect foreign nationals and therefore be discriminatory. 
[normal]In 
[normal]this way, the proposals undermi
[normal]ne the principle of equity in 
[normal]access to legal aid, 
[normal]which requires special measures to be taken to 
[normal]ensure meaningful access to legal aid for “
[normal]stateless persons, asylum seekers, foreign citizens, migrants and migrant workers, refugees and internally displace
[normal]d persons
[normal]”
[normal].
[normal] We are concerned at the proposed changes which 
[normal]will: restrict access to justice for vulnerable immigration detainees; 
[normal]remove funds for 
[normal]mentally ill detainees to challenge the lawfulness of their detention; and 
[normal]not assist 
[normal]failed asylum seekers 
[normal]with further representations
[normal].
[normal] 
