[normal]In its reply to our response the government argued
[normal] that:
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]              
[normal]‘HMIP’s annual report contains a comparison of survey scores of prisoners who consider themselves to have a disability and those who do not; these data include prisoners with a physical disability as well as those with mental health issues and/or learning 
[normal]disabilities. HMIP’s 2011-12 Annual Report (latest available) indicates the following: 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q. Is it easy to get a complaints [bold]form[bold]? [bold]Disabled – 82% Yes 
[normal]Non-disabled – 83% Yes 
[normal]Q. Have you made a complaint? [bold]Disabled – 55% Yes 
[normal]Non-disabled – 46% Yes 
[normal]Q. Is t[bold]here a member of staff in this prison that you can turn to for help if you have a problem? [bold]Disabled – 76% Yes 
[normal]Non-disabled – 75% Yes 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]              
[normal]We acknowledge that HMIP’s response to the consultation contained data indicating that prisoners with mental health is
[normal]sues and/or learning disabilities (as well as prisoners generally) did not have confidence in the complaints system and that outcomes were poor. However, the information from the 2011-12 Annual Report referred to above suggests a different picture in terms
[normal] of accessibility, willingness to use the system and the potential for reasonable adjustments to be made when comparing disabled and non-disabled prisoners. Although respondents had concerns around potential impacts on these prisoners we consider the proce
[normal]sses set out in PSI 02/2012 (Prisoner complaints), PSI 32/2011 (Ensuring equality) and 75/2011 (Residential services) are sufficient to 
[normal]ensure they are able to make effective use of the complaints system and access the other alternative means of redress.’
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]28. 
